│                                                                             │
│   return true;                                                              │
│ };                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ The poison check only verifies that the first operand is zero, but doesn't  │
│ check if the negation itself can produce poison. For `sub nsw 0, x`, it can │
│ produce poison when x is the minimum signed value.                          │
│                                                                             │
│ When `AllowPoison=false`, we should return false if the negation operation  │
│ can produce poison.                                                         │
│                                                                             │
│ For integer negation with NSW, it produces poison exactly when the input is │
│ the minimum signed value of its type.                                       │
│                                                                             │
│ So we need to add a check: if `AllowPoison=false` and the operation is `sub │
│ nsw 0, x`, then we need to ensure that x cannot be the minimum signed       │
│ value.                                                                      │
│                                                                             │
│ However, this is difficult to determine statically in general. A safer      │
│ approach is to simply not allow the swap optimization when                  │
│ `AllowPoison=false` for NSW operations, or to always fall back to the       │
│ general negation method when `AllowPoison=false`.                           │
│                                                                             │
│ Actually, looking at the broader context, the issue is that the swap        │
│ optimization is fundamentally incompatible with `AllowPoison=false` because │
│ it changes which operand is selected, and thus changes the poison           │
│ semantics.                                                                  │
│                                                                             │
│ The correct fix is to remove the swap optimization entirely when            │
│ `AllowPoison=false`, and always use the general method of negating both     │
│ operands.                                                                   │
│                                                                             │
│ Let me implement this fix by modifying the negator code to skip the swap    │
│ optimization when `AllowPoison=false`.                                      │
│                                                                             │
│ ```bash                                                                     │
│ sed -i 's/if (isKnownNegation(I->getOperand(1), I->getOperand(2),           │
│ \/\/NeedNSW=\/\*false\*/, \/\/AllowPoison=\/\*false\*/)) {/if (false &&     │
│ isKnownNegation(I->getOperand(1), I->getOperand(2), \/*NeedNSW=*\/false,    │
│ \/*AllowPoison=*\/false)) {/'                                               │
│ /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineNeg │
│ ator.cpp                                                                    │
│ ```                                                                         │
